cs.IT, cs.COMM, cs.SI, cs.NI, cs.DS 

The paper deals with capacity results in communication systems, specifically the "writing on dirty paper" channel. It discusses the impact of channel knowledge on interference pre-coding and proposes improvements for discrete channel states. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). It also involves communication systems and wireless environments, which suggests cs.COMM (Communications and Networking) as another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions state decoding and input constellations, which are related to signal processing and machine learning, indicating cs.SI (Signal Processing) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper deals with fast fading processes, which are related to network infrastructure, suggesting cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) as a possible sub-category.
